title: 50 Years Since Whitlam Dismissal, Neo-Nazis Disturb Service, Prince William On Parenting | 10 News+
description: Fifty years ago, on November 11, 1975, Australia faced its biggest political crisis when the Governor-General Sir John Kerr sensationally sacked the then-Labor Prime Minister Gough Whitlam. Current PM Anthony Albanese describes the incident as a “partisan, political ambush” with “no legitimate pretext”. Former PM Paul Keating says the dismissal was “in every respect a coup”. 10 News+ spoke to journalist Leigh Hatcher, who was on the steps of Old Parliament House on that fateful day when the crisis occurred.  The nation stopped at 11am on this Remembrance Day to pay silent tribute to all who have given their lives to serve Australia. Melbourne’s service, at the Shrine of Remembrance, was marred by a disturbing and disrespectful sight. A group of men from a Neo-Nazi organisation held up a White Australia flag at the Shrine, and were promptly moved on by police.  Three Chinese astronauts are extending their stay in space after rogue debris hit their return capsule destined for Earth. The trio were nearing the end of their six months in orbit as part of the Shenzhou-20 mission. While the damage is being investigated, the astronauts are now docked at Tiangong, China’s space station, as experts work out how and when to get them home.  Prince William has opened up about the struggles of being a parent, in a rare and candid interview with Brazilian media. He spoke about the challenges of managing screen time, and his children’s interaction with online, digital spaces, while revealing that his eldest son Prince George still isn’t allowed a mobile phone. title: WA Windsurfer Survives With Bitten Board After Great White Shark Attack | 10 News
description: A WA windsurfer has told how he fought off a 3.5 metre great white shark as it attacked him in off the states south west. title: China’s Hongqi Bridge Partially Collapses After Massive Landslide | 10 News
description: A 758-metre-long bridge has partially collapsed in China’s southwestern province of Sichuan after a landslide struck the mountainside where it was built.  Dramatic video shows a large section of the bridge breaking away and plunging into the river below on Tuesday just months after opening.  The local government said police closed Hongqi bridge to all traffic on Monday afternoon after cracks appeared on nearby slopes and roads, and shifts were seen in the terrain of a mountain before conditions worsened yesterday.  The bridge was completed earlier this year as part of a major highway project linking central China with Tibet. title: Suicide Bombing Near Islamabad Court Kills 12 As Pakistani Taliban Claims Responsibility | 10 News
description: At least 12 people have been killed and 27 injured in a suicide bombing outside a court in Pakistan’s capital, Islamabad.   The attacker reportedly tried to enter the court complex but, after failing to do so, detonated near a police vehicle, setting cars ablaze and sending crowds running in panic.   The Pakistani Taliban has claimed responsibility for the blast, which shattered windows and damaged nearby government buildings.   Prime Minister Shehbaz Sharif condemned the “reprehensible” attack and vowed to bring those responsible to justice, as authorities investigate links to a wider surge in militant violence across Pakistan’s northwest, near the Afghan border.
